ublic company or comparable category captures all three. An analyst must either (i) split the segment and apply different multiples to each sub-business (introducing allocation subjectivity), or (ii) apply a single blended multiple that averages across categories with very different risk/return profiles.\n\n### (b) Loss-making, forcing reliance on EV/Revenue with an enormous multiple spread\nBecause Segment Adjusted EBITDA is **negative $(1,237)M**, EV/EBITDA is mathematically meaningless. The analyst is forced to use EV/Revenue, but the relevant comparable revenue multiples span a **17x range**:\n- Snap: 1.4x revenue\n- Vertiv: 9.6x revenue\n- Reddit: 11.5x revenue\n- CoreWeave: 23.8x revenue\n\nSelecting any point in this range is highly subjective and swings the implied AI enterprise value from ~$4.5B (at 1.4x) to ~$76B (at 23.8x).\n\n### (c) No public LLM pure-play\nGrok is the segment\'s flagship product, but the most directly relevant comparables — OpenAI and Anthropic — are private. Their reported valuations reflect late-stage private rounds that may embed liquidity discounts, strategic premiums, or momentum pricing not subject to public-market discipline. There is no way to triangulate a "market" LLM multiple from public filings.\n\n### (d) Unprecedented strategic optionality\nThe S-1 discloses plans to deploy **orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028**, with a long-term goal of launching **100 gigawatts of compute to space annually**. No public company has ever attempted space-based AI compute, so there is no precedent for valuing this optionality. Traditional comparables (CoreWeave, Vertiv) are terrestrial and cannot price the orbital compute thesis.\n\n### (e) Vertical-integration premium is unquantifiable via standalone peers\nThe segment\'s strategic logic rests on combining Grok (LLM) + X (real-time data) + compute infrastructure + Starlink connectivity + orbital compute. This vertical integration creates synergies and data advantages that no standalone comparable possesses, making it impossible to derive an appropriate conglomerate premium from public peers.\n\n### (f) Early-stage with multi-year investment horizon\nThe S-1 explicitly states the company expects a **"multi-year investment horizon before sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA,"** with Segment Adjusted EBITDA deteriorating from +$347M in 2024 to $(1,237)M in 2025. This negative trajectory and uncertain path to profitability makes any DCF or multiple-based approach highly sensitive to assumptions about future capex and revenue ramp.\n\n### Contrast with Space and Connectivity\n- **Space** has one clear pure-play public comparable (Rocket Lab); the ambiguity is mainly about scale mismatch and the Starship option value, not about which comparable *category* to use.\n- **Connectivity** has a well-defined comparable category (satellite communications operators: Iridium, Globalstar, Viasat, Gogo) with established EV/EBITDA benchmarks; the ambiguity is about the magnitude of Starlink\'s growth premium, not about category selection.\n\nOnly the **AI segment** forces the analyst to choose among multiple, mutually inconsistent comparable categories, with no public benchmark for the segment\'s most important product (Grok), while the segment is loss-making and includes unprecedented strategic optionality (orbital compute). This makes it the segment with the greatest comparable-selection ambiguity.\n\n---\n\n## Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) — Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation, segment revenue, AI segment revenue breakdown, balance sheet"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1819994/000181999426000013/rklb-20251231.htm",\n      "name": "Rocket Lab Corp (RKLB) 10-K for FY2025 (filed Feb 26, 2026) — Revenue, operating loss, shares outstanding"\n 